 future (although it will be in the Italian system over my dead body) I won't suddenly lose interest. &#10;The majority of my friends see their obligation as ongoing and invest huge amounts of time and effort in the process. They don’t home educate. &#10;I participate in many forums that are focused on mainstream education. The attitude you describe is a million miles from what I have observed. &#10;Sweeping generalizations are irritating and inaccurate.&#10;That also applies when home educators make them about parents who use schools."/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="810" language="en" documentId="1156" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="boscoticino" date="29 July 2010 3:06pm" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6885389" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="1" thumbsDown="0" origId="1156" notes="" title="Home education: precious, not dangerous"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="151"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="152" end="177"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="178" end="186"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="187" end="387"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55" sofa="1" begin="388" end="531"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="59" sofa="1" begin="532" end="675"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="63" sofa="1" begin="676" end="731"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="67" sofa="1" begin="732" end="810"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51 55 59 63 67"/></xmi:XMI>